      "content": "The square root of $16900$ is exactly $130$. Now, that's the total impedance ($\\text{Z}$) of your circuit, which is $130\\ \\Omega$. You can find the current ($I$) using Ohm's Law, but for AC circuits, we use the AC version: $I = V / Z$.\n\nSo, you take your source voltage ($V$), which is $120\\text{V}$, and divide it by the total impedance ($\\text{Z}$), which is $130\\ \\Omega$. $I = 120\\text{V} / 130\\ \\Omega$. That gives you a current of approximately $0.923$ Amperes.\n\n*A little side note:* Finding the current is just like finding the length of a long, winding path for a little, determined little creature. If the path is too long (high impedance), the little creature has to push harder, or in this case, the current has to be smaller, even if the push (voltage) is the same. It's all about how much resistance the path throws up in its way.\n\nDon'",
